  "text": "Another concept that has gained traction in simulation pedagogic research is cognitive load, drawing from developments in cognitive psychology (Sweller, 2003; Sweller et al. 2011 ). The imposed cognitive load is dependent on the number of elements with which the learners must deal simultaneously. In simulation education, cognitive load may be managed in two directions. Simple (low-load) tasks such as routine procedures can be 'made harder' by introducing time pressures. Conversely, complex scenarios such as acute emergency situations that might overwhelm students can be brought to a manageable load level by removing or ignoring particular features [CITATION_1] .",
